---
import Capability from '../Capability.astro';
---

<section id="capabilities" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      The capabilities
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      What a meta-harness adds
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">
      The category is new and the industry is moving fast. Not every
      meta-harness implements every feature below. But a pattern is emerging.
      Each capability is a boundary that agents run into, and that
      meta-harnesses break.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="mt-16 space-y-16">
    <Capability
      id="harness-swapping"
      index="01"
      title="Harness swapping"
      analogy="Like hiring a specialist instead of asking one generalist to do everything."
      parallel="routing. Next.js decides which handler serves each request; the meta-harness decides which harness serves each task."
      vizLabel="a mid-session swap, the Claude Code tile lifting out and Codex dropping in while the session log persists"
    >
      <p>
        The most obvious one. Pick between harnesses, swap them, and compose
        them in a single session. Maybe your provider is down. Maybe different
        repos standardize on different harnesses. Maybe one harness is simply
        better at a given task than another. Swapping and composing let you
        <mark>route each piece of work to the right agent</mark> instead of
        forcing one to do everything.
      </p>
    </Capability>

    <Capability
      id="permissions"
      index="02"
      title="Permissions and guardrails"
      analogy="House rules everyone follows, not sticky notes on each desk."
      vizLabel="one org rule defined once, three parallel session lanes, one lane pausing for approval as it trips the shared rule"
    >
      <p>
        The permission model of a bare harness is too crude and too personal. It
        asks one user to approve one action. Organizations want nuanced rules
        that everyone adheres to, set per team, per repo, or per role, like
        requiring explicit verification before a new npm dependency is added, or
        blocking writes to certain paths. Those rules have to live outside any
        single harness, which requires the organization itself to exist as a
        first-class thing. A meta-harness
        <mark>lifts guardrails from the individual to the org</mark>.
      </p>
    </Capability>

    <Capability
      id="materialization"
      index="03"
      title="Repository materialization"
      analogy="Walking into a kitchen with everything already prepped, not shopping before you can cook."
      parallel="server-side rendering. The framework does the setup work ahead of time so the thing arrives ready to use."
      vizLabel="a prompt going in on the left, a ready workspace assembling on the right: repo cloned, dependencies installed, dev server up"
    >
      <p>
        When you type codex or claude in a folder, that folder already has to
        exist and the environment already has to be ready. Materialization is
        the process of setting up the environment where the
        agent can do useful work. Cloud agents implement a basic version of it;
        local harnesses do very little. Think of it as the step that takes your
        prompt, provisions the relevant source code, installs the necessary
        dependencies, runs setup scripts, and gets the agent going,
        <mark>all before the first token of real work</mark>.
      </p>
    </Capability>

    <Capability
      id="cross-repo"
      index="04"
      title="Cross-repo reach"
      analogy="One agent that reads the whole map, not one that knows a single street."
      vizLabel="a dependency graph of repos, a change originating in one node and rippling outward, consumer repos lighting up as coordinated PRs"
    >
      <p>
        Your organization's code lives in more than one repository. To get the
        relevant context, the agent often needs to look across several of them,
        private or open source. This lets it align a change in one repo with its
        consumers in another, trace how a type flows through the stack, and
        understand who depends on the code it's about to touch.
      </p>
      <p>
        But reading is only half the story. The other half is producing
        cross-repo changes, validating them downstream against the repos that
        consume them, and <mark>coordinating the resulting PRs so they land
        together</mark> instead of breaking each other.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400">
        Regular harnesses offer a basic mechanism for adding multiple roots, but
        it doesn't scale beyond simple cases. A harness really works in folders
        of files, not repos. It has no notion of a repository, of how repos
        relate, or of a code change as distinct from a PR, even though one change
        can span several PRs across several repos. The set of repos has to be
        known in advance. It has to be set up by hand. The agent naively pulls
        every repo into scope at once. And there is no coordination across the
        multiple PRs that a cross-repo change produces.
      </p>
    </Capability>

    <Capability
      id="multiplayer"
      index="05"
      title="Multiplayer"
      analogy="A shared document, not files emailed back and forth."
      vizLabel="a session graph, a second cursor joining the same live session, branches from past sessions feeding in"
    >
      <p>
        More interesting changes usually pull in another person to contribute or
        review. You work on them together. Harnesses provide very basic session
        sharing, if any, and generally no real way to collaborate.
      </p>
      <p>
        Meta-harnesses let different people contribute to the same session, some
        in true multiplayer mode, some not. That also means you can
        <mark>resume each other's sessions</mark>, review them, or reference
        them in future work.
      </p>
    </Capability>

    <Capability
      id="durability"
      index="06"
      title="Session durability"
      analogy="A saved game with cloud sync, not a run you lose the moment you close the console."
      vizLabel="a session card saved on one laptop, the laptop closing, the session reopening intact on a second machine days later"
    >
      <p>
        By default, sessions are local. They can be resumed, but only if the
        environment they were set up in (git worktrees and all) is still around.
        In practice that means you can't count on a session surviving a long
        gap, you can't pick it up on a different machine, and another person
        can't pick it up at all. Today the only durable output of a session is
        the pull request. <mark>The PR is durable, the session is not.</mark>
      </p>
      <p>
        A meta-harness makes sessions durable, preserving them so they can be
        restored at any point in the future, on any machine, by anyone with
        access. Once a session is reified you can name it, reference it in a
        future prompt so the agent pulls in everything it needs without
        re-explaining, reconstruct it on another machine to poke at it, and
        compose it into new work.
      </p>
    </Capability>

    <Capability
      id="memory"
      index="07"
      title="Memory"
      analogy="The map, not the terrain. Memory orients you fast, but you navigate the ground in front of you, and when they disagree, the terrain wins."
      vizLabel="a session graph feeding a memory layer, a new session pulling relevant past sessions in as context"
    >
      <p>
        By default, agents have basic local personal memory, if any. There is no
        notion of institutional memory: the accumulated, team-shared
        understanding of how your organization works and what it needs.
      </p>
      <p>
        Memory splits along two axes.
        <mark>Episodic memory</mark> is the record of specific work: which
        sessions ran, what they touched, what they decided, and crucially why
        one approach was chosen over another.
        <mark>Semantic memory</mark> is the distilled knowledge that outlives
        any single session: conventions, architecture, the shape of the system.
        Both come in short-term and long-term forms.
      </p>
      <p>
        The two feed each other. A repository graph of what the code actually is
        and a session graph of what was done to it influence one another, so
        memory stays grounded in the system rather than in stale notes. Docs
        rot and code does not. A meta-harness captures work as it happens, so a
        new session can start grounded in what the org already knows instead of
        relearning it every time. Because sessions are related to each other in
        a session graph, new work starts by borrowing from the sessions it is
        related to, so you never start from scratch.
      </p>
    </Capability>
  </div>
</section>
